'''Woltz''':(old Saxon ''Voltz'', Swedish ''Woitz'') is a German, low german word originated from the original ruinic words. Similar to the old Germanic words like Vogt, Hine, Hammer, Hiest, and others, it refers to one of the original names of the germanic people starting with the southern Jutland Saxons mixing with the Teutons.

==Word Defintion==
During the Barbarian invasion of southern Europe this word often ment, young leader, or young warrior. Other traces of this word is similar to Junge Fuhrer.

==Name==
This name is normally or oftenly found with an extra -en at the end or -dorff to make Woltzen, making it plural for young leaders, and -dorff making it mean young leader town. This name is one of the original names of the Germanic peoples.